Probably a more useful test suite would be one that takes the names of 
the test methods to run as its ctor argument, then you can run arbitrary 
sets of them, e.g.

   ArbitraryTestSuite extends TestSuite {
      TestSuite(Class testCase, String[] cases) {
	...
	}
}

Constructing test suites is really something better done dynamically or 
from a script, rather than hard-coded.

T.


On Thursday, April 4, 2002, at 08:15 PM, Mike Clark wrote:

&gt; pantinori wrote:
&gt;
&gt;&gt; Is there a way to specify in the ANT build.xml target for junit, that
&gt;&gt; certain test methods in a TestCase class should be executed.  I have
&gt;&gt; several test methods in a TestCase that need to be executed several
&gt;&gt; times and in the proper order.  I was looking at the ANT
&gt;&gt; documentation on &lt;batchtests&gt; and the fileset node can only indicate
&gt;&gt; classes, not a list of tests that should go into a TestSuite.
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;m not aware of a dynamic way of achieving this, unfortunately.
&gt;
&gt; Of course, you could write a TestSuite that includes the test methods of
&gt; interest:
&gt;
&gt; public class MySuite extends TestCase {
&gt;
&gt;     public static Test suite() {
&gt;         TestSuite suite = new TestSuite();
&gt;         suite.addTest(new TestCase1(&quot;testSomething&quot;));
&gt;         suite.addTest(new TestCase2(&quot;testSomething&quot;));
&gt;         suite.addTest(new TestCase3(&quot;testSomething&quot;));
&gt;         ...
&gt;         return suite;
&gt;     }
&gt;
&gt; But you probably already thought of that...
